Question 2
How can a parent component set properties on its child components in LWC? Provide a code example.
Companies that asked this: Salesforce, TCS, Infosys, Accenture, Wipro

Answer:
Parent components set properties on child components by using the @api decorator to expose public properties in the child, then binding values through attributes in the parent template.
child Component (Exposes Public Properties):

contactCard.js

import { LightningElement, api } from 'lwc';
 
export default class ContactCard extends LightningElement {
    @api contactName;
    @api contactEmail;
    @api isActive;
    @api recordCount;
}

contactCard.html

<template>
    <div class="contact-card">
        <h3>{contactName}</h3>
        <p>Email: {contactEmail}</p>
        <p>Status: {isActive}</p>
        <p>Records: {recordCount}</p>
    </div>
</template>

Parent Component (Sets Properties on Child):

contactList.js

import { LightningElement } from 'lwc';
 
export default class ContactList extends LightningElement {
    contact = {
        name: 'John Doe',
        email: 'john@example.com'
    };
    
    activeStatus = true;
    totalRecords = 25;
}
contactList.html

<template>
    <c-contact-card 
        contact-name={contact.name}
        contact-email={contact.email}
        is-active={activeStatus}
        record-count={totalRecords}>
    </c-contact-card>
</template>

Key Points:

JavaScript properties use camelCase (contactName)

HTML attributes use kebab-case (contact-name)

Primitive values (string, number, boolean) are preferred

Data flows one-way from parent to child

Child components treat received properties as read-only



Interview Tips:

Emphasize the @api decorator makes properties public

Mention the camelCase vs kebab-case naming convention

Show understanding that data flows one-way from parent to child

Explain that child components should treat properties as read-only

Demonstrate that property updates in parent automatically update child
